            <div data-toc-linked id="outputs" class="cs:chunk">
                {{ elements.csTitle('h3', 'Outputs') }}
                <div class="cs:content">
                    <p>
                        At Rewatch, Mike rebuilt the entire marketing website, lead a redesign of the visual identity, and did a countless number of other design and dev related marketing tasks that are too long to list here without you getting bored reading it. ðŸ”¨
                    </p>
                    <ul class="relative flex flex:col gap:32 md:gap:48 w:100p">
                        <li class="flex flex:col gap:8 w:100p pl:20 sm:pl:32 border-l:1 border:primary-rg">
                            <h4 class="font:md sm:font:lg color:ink-3 mt:n8">
                                Website rebuild
                            </h4>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1 mb:4">
                                When Mike joined Rewatch, the site had a handful of pain points. First and foremost, the site's code lived within the same repo as the product and was using bits and pieces of the product and alongside custom stuff making it difficult to know what else changes made on the site could effect. The site was using Jekyll as an SSG â€“ which is simple enough, but it's unnecessary to manage ruby on a marketing site that doesn't use it anywhere else. The blog and changelog were being managed manually through markdown files on GitHub. 
                            </p>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1 mb:4">
                                Mike rebuilt using a handful of new tools. Knowing, in the future, he would not be the only person working on this site and that projects needed to be executed fast, Mike made an effort to make the codebase as simple and quick as possible to setup, understand, and start building on.
                            </p>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1 mb:4">
                                To start, Mike opted to use 11ty as an SSG due to it's similarity to Jekyll and it's ease of use. Being able to solely run NodeJS without having to worry about Ruby was great. 11ty has great docs and a strong community, which makes getting support and troubleshooting on-the-fly a breeze. It also allowed the site to be primarily written in plain ol' HTML, which most any developer can dive right into and write quickly.
                            </p>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1 mb:4">
                                For a CMS, Mike chose to go with NetlifyCMS. Again, it is extremely easy to configure/change/work with and worked well with the existing markdown files. Mike personally loves it due to how it works with Git/Github and in that it prevents a companies content from ever being held captive by proprietary CMS software.
                            </p>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1 mb:n4">
                                The approach to CSS was the biggest hang-up during this project. At first, Mike used custom SCSS as it was what he was most familiar with â€“ though after some feedback from his manager, opted to align with the product's approach to styling using UniformCSS, a sass utility generator and framework. This decision made the front-end code between the marketing site and product look extremely similar, making code reviews and working between the two easier.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex flex:col gap:8 w:100p pl:20 sm:pl:32 border-l:1 border:primary-rg">
                            <h4 class="font:md sm:font:lg color:ink-3 mt:n8">
                                Brand redesign
                            </h4>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1">
                                As mentioned earlier, when Mike joined Rewatch, the brand was highly directed toward engaging an engineering audience. At the time, it made sense. Initially, Rewatch's primary growth came from helping eliminate synchronous meetings for engineering teams at enterprise orgs.
                            </p>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1">
                                The challenge Mike and marketing team faced was uncovering what audience would drive the next wave of growth at Rewatch and updating the visual identity to target them. However, based on sales, this was impossible as there wasn't a consistent persona. After determining this approach to direction wouldn't work, we looked inward vs. outward. Mike's partner in marketing created a poll <span class="color:ink-1 italic">(with direct references various styling and visual approaches)</span> that was taken by leadership team, then reviewed together to understand how the greater team viewed the future of the company.
                            </p>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1">
                                From there, Mike took the findings and quickly threw together, and shared, a deploy preview showing what the homepage could look like with those agreed upon styles applied to Rewatch. After getting the green light, Mike applied these styles across the marketing site and other marketing assets.
                            </p>
                            <p class="font:sm sm:font:md color:ink-1 mb:n4">
                                Fortunately, at this point, the marketing site had been rebuilt and optimized for rapid change â€“ giving Mike the ability to update the entire visual identity of Rewatch in less <span class="space:nowrap">than two weeks.</span>
                            </p>
                        </li>
